  "prompt": "What 6/9 mean in eyesight?",
  "response": "In eyesight terminology, particularly when assessing visual acuity, \"6/9\" indicates the clarity or sharpness of vision. This is based on the Snellen chart, which is a standard tool used in eye exams.\n\n- The first number in the ratio (6) represents the distance, in meters, at which the test is conducted.\n- The second number (9) indicates the distance at which a person with normal eyesight can correctly identify the same line of letters on the chart.\n\nSo, if you have a visual acuity of 6/9:\n- You can see at 6 meters what a person with normal vision can see at 9 meters.\nIt's indicative of slightly lower visual acuity compared to \"normal\" vision (which is often represented as 6/6).",
